[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Protocol-Grounded Conversational Triage With Conservative-By-Default Decision Logic
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Symptom-Triage Has Stayed Phone-Centric (And Why Most Web Symptom Checkers Failed)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Symptom triage, as a workflow, has been a phone-centric problem for the last fifty years and has been done by experienced nurses for almost all of that time. The reason is structural. Symptom triage is the process of taking a patient's free-form description of what they are feeling, asking the focused follow-up questions that disambiguate the clinically-relevant features, and matching the resulting feature constellation to an institution-sanctioned recommendation about what the patient should do next. The questions are not generic. The questions for chest pain are different from the questions for headache. The questions for headache in a 78-year-old with hypertension are different from the questions for headache in a 28-year-old with no history. The recommendations are not binary. The recommendation is not "go to the ER" or "stay home"; the recommendation is one of several appropriate care levels (self-care, telehealth, primary care, urgent care, ED, 911) calibrated to the acuity of the presentation and the patient's specific context. The clinical judgment lives in the calibration; it has lived in nurses' heads, supplemented by paper protocols, since the workflow began.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital symptom checkers, roughly the early 2000s through the late 2010s, tried to systematize this with explicit decision-tree software. The patient clicked through a tree of yes/no questions and received a recommendation at the leaf. The trees were sometimes built by clinicians and sometimes purchased from vendors who claimed they were. Several of the major-vendor symptom checkers received high-profile evaluations in the medical literature. The findings were not flattering. <!-- TODO: verify; published evaluations of digital symptom checkers including Semigran et al. 2015 in BMJ, Hill et al. 2020 in MJA, Ceney et al. 2021 in PLOS ONE, and others have documented variable accuracy with both over-triage and under-triage failure modes; specific accuracy figures depend on the symptom checker, the population, and the methodology --> The decision-tree symptom checkers had three structural problems. First, they could only ask the questions encoded in the tree, which meant they could not follow up on what the patient had actually said. Second, the patient's free-text description of symptoms had to be coerced into the tree's pre-defined symptom categories, which destroyed nuance and produced wrong matches. Third, the trees were rigid; if the patient's presentation did not fit cleanly into a tree branch, the tree silently picked a branch and produced a recommendation that did not actually correspond to the patient's situation. The patients who used these tools mostly did not trust them; the clinicians who reviewed their outputs mostly did not trust them either.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2015 to 2022, layered machine-learning models on top of the symptom inputs. The architecture varied (some used neural networks, some used Bayesian networks, some used probabilistic graphical models with named conditions as nodes), but the user-facing pattern was similar: enter symptoms, get a ranked differential or a recommended action. Several of these tools secured significant funding, partnered with health systems and insurers, and faced public criticism over both their clinical accuracy and the regulatory claims their marketing departments made about them. <!-- TODO: verify; the trajectory of differential-generating symptom checkers including products from Babylon Health, Buoy Health, Ada, K Health, Mayo Clinic, Isabel Healthcare, and others has been documented in trade press and academic literature; specific accuracy figures and regulatory actions vary by product and time period --> Some of them retrenched their scope to lower-acuity guidance. Some of them shut down. The category became a cautionary tale in healthcare AI circles, often cited as the example of "things that look like they should work but require careful clinical and regulatory engineering to actually deliver value safely."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can carry on a coherent conversation while sticking to a structured task. A conversational triage interview, conducted by an LLM that has been carefully scoped to follow institution-validated protocols, can ask the focused follow-up questions a nurse would ask, capture the patient's nuanced responses without forcing them into pre-defined categories, and produce a recommendation that is grounded in the same protocol the nurse would have used. The LLM's value is concentrated in the conversational layer; the clinical logic still lives in the protocol. The LLM is a better front-end to a triage protocol than a decision-tree was, and the protocol is the part that matters clinically.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "click through a decision tree" to "have a conversation that follows the protocol." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the patient experience (asking a natural-language question and getting a specific recommendation in minutes rather than waiting on hold or guessing alone), the safety floor (the protocol-driven logic plus the human-escalation path catch the high-acuity cases that ad-hoc patient self-triage misses), and the operational savings (the routine triage volume is handled at the bot tier, freeing the nurse line for the cases that benefit from clinical judgment).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Triage Bot Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A triage bot is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context (age, sex, basic chart history, current medications, current conditions, recent visits if relevant), and access to a structured library of institution-sanctioned triage protocols. The LLM conducts the conversation. The protocols, modeled as data, encode the clinical logic. The tools handle the deterministic actions: looking up the right protocol for the symptom, retrieving the relevant chart context, computing acuity scores from clinical-decision-rule inputs, escalating to a nurse line, posting a recommendation event for downstream operations, logging crisis-detection events to the appropriate response pathway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation has a structure even though the patient does not see it. The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The greeting and disclosure.** Critical for the triage bot specifically because patients have variable familiarity with what a chatbot can and cannot do, and the disclosure has to set expectations clearly without scaring the patient out of using the tool. Identifies as a chatbot, states scope (informational triage; not a diagnosis; not a replacement for a clinician), notes that the questions are based on the same protocols the institution's nurses use, names the human-escalation pathway, and reinforces the 911-redirect for emergencies.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Crisis-and-emergency screening up front.** Before the protocol-driven triage starts, the bot screens for explicit emergency presentations. If the patient says "I'm having chest pain right now," the bot does not start a structured chest-pain protocol from scratch; it asks two or three high-yield questions to confirm the emergency presentation and routes immediately to 911 with stay-on-the-line guidance. If the patient says "I'm thinking about hurting myself," the bot routes immediately to 988 or the institution's crisis line. The screening is layered with the protocol selection rather than gated behind it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Symptom identification and protocol selection.** The patient's free-form initial complaint is mapped to the most appropriate triage protocol. "Chest pressure" maps to the chest-pain protocol. "Bad headache" maps to the headache protocol. "I think I might have a UTI" maps to the urinary-symptoms protocol. The mapping is done by the LLM with retrieval over the protocol library; ambiguous mappings (a patient with both chest pain and shortness of breath could route to either protocol) trigger a clarifying question. Multi-symptom presentations are handled by selecting the highest-acuity-eligible protocol and noting the others for cross-reference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured protocol-driven questioning.** Once the protocol is selected, the bot conducts the protocol's question sequence in conversational form. The protocol specifies the canonical questions; the bot may rephrase them for clarity, ask them in a slightly different order based on what the patient has already volunteered, and follow up on ambiguous answers. Critically, the bot does not skip protocol questions and does not invent new ones; the protocol is the spine, and the conversation hangs from it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Acuity scoring and recommendation.** When the protocol's questions have been answered, the bot computes the protocol's recommendation. For some protocols, this is a deterministic mapping from the answer set to the recommendation. For others, it is a clinical-decision rule (HEART score, Wells score, Centor score for streptococcal pharyngitis, Ottawa ankle rules) computed by a tool and used as input to the recommendation logic. The recommendation is one of a small set of care levels: self-care at home with monitoring, telehealth visit, primary care visit (today, in 24-48 hours, or routine), urgent care visit, emergency department visit, or 911 call. <!-- TODO: verify; the HEART score, Wells score, Centor score, Ottawa ankle rules, and similar clinical-decision rules are well-established in the literature with documented sensitivity and specificity profiles; the specific protocol implementations and care-level mappings vary by institution -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recommendation delivery with disclaimers and instructions.** The bot delivers the recommendation in plain English with the appropriate disclaimers, the rationale (briefly), and the next-step instructions. For high-acuity recommendations (911, ED), the instructions include immediate safety guidance (stay seated, do not drive yourself, call someone to be with you) and any institution-approved interim measures (the aspirin-for-suspected-MI example earlier; the bot's handling of these specifics depends entirely on the institution's clinical protocol and its FDA-strategy positioning). For low-acuity recommendations (self-care), the instructions include red-flag symptoms that should trigger re-triage and a path to re-engage with the bot or the nurse line.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Nurse-line escalation.** The bot escalates to a human nurse when the protocol calls for it (some protocols escalate at specific decision points), when the bot's confidence in any step is below threshold, when the patient's presentation does not fit cleanly into any protocol, when the patient explicitly requests a human, or when any layer (input safety, output safety) flags an issue. The escalation hands off the conversation transcript, the protocol selected, the answer set captured, the computed recommendation, and any uncertainty markers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-channel continuity.** A patient who starts on chat and needs to switch to a nurse phone call should not have to start over. The escalation includes the conversation context as a structured payload that the receiving nurse can read in seconds. The patient's wait time at the nurse line is bounded; the institution's commitment to the patient is that the bot will catch high-acuity cases regardless of nurse-line availability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Audit and follow-up.** Every triage conversation produces an audit record (transcript, protocol used, recommendation produced, recommendation delivered, patient response, escalation status). The audit feeds compliance review, clinical-quality review, and outcome-tracking. Where the institution has the capability, the bot's recommendation is correlated with the patient's actual care utilization (did they actually go to the ED, the urgent care, did they have a follow-up encounter) for ongoing protocol-and-bot calibration. <!-- TODO: verify; outcome-correlation for symptom-triage tools requires institutional data integration and is operationally significant work; specific implementations vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Triage Bot
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some triage information, and have it conduct triage. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical and regulatory consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no view of the patient's specific clinical context.** Without the patient's age, sex, current medications, current conditions, and basic recent history as input, the LLM cannot calibrate the recommendation appropriately. "Chest pain in a 25-year-old with no history" is a different protocol entry-point than "chest pain in a 65-year-old with hypertension and diabetes." The chart-context tools (age, sex, problem list, medication list, recent visits) are non-optional inputs. The bot is not blind to the patient's record; it is grounded in it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model hallucinates clinical content when grounding is weak.** If the protocols are not retrieved with strict citation grounding, the LLM produces plausible-sounding clinical recommendations that are wrong for the institution's actual protocol. Worse, the LLM may produce recommendations that contradict the standard of care. The protocol RAG layer with strict citation grounding is non-negotiable. The bot cites the protocol it is following, the version of the protocol that is in effect, and the specific decision points from the protocol that drove the recommendation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no reliable theory of conservative-by-default escalation.** Without explicit guardrails, the LLM tends toward "let me try to help you figure this out" responses that under-triage when they should escalate. The protocols are designed with conservative bias (when in doubt, escalate to higher acuity); the LLM's default helpfulness instinct can erode that bias. The architectural pattern is to encode the conservative-default policy in the protocol logic, run the recommendation through deterministic computation, and have the LLM only deliver and explain the recommendation rather than originate it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model cannot reliably recognize a true emergency in the middle of a conversation.** A patient who starts with "I just have a question about my back" and then mentions, three turns in, that they have lost the ability to feel their legs and have lost bladder control is presenting cauda equina syndrome (a 911 case) inside a conversation that started as a low-acuity question. <!-- TODO: verify; cauda equina syndrome is a recognized neurosurgical emergency; specific clinical features include saddle anesthesia, urinary retention or incontinence, and progressive lower-extremity weakness --> The bot's emergency screening runs continuously, not just at the start of the conversation. Every patient utterance is screened for emergency keywords and feature constellations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no audit trail of what was asked, what was answered, what was retrieved, and what was recommended.** A regulated triage answer requires showing the work: the protocol consulted, the question sequence, the patient's responses, the computed acuity, the basis for the recommendation. The structured-data ledger plus the conversation log are the audit surface. Without it, the recommendation is unreviewable, the case is impossible to defend if outcomes are bad, and the regulatory position is untenable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems.** Clinical-decision rules (HEART, Wells, Centor, Ottawa, others) compute scores from structured inputs. The LLM does this arithmetic poorly. The clinical-decision-rule tool encapsulates the computation; the LLM gathers the inputs through the conversation, calls the tool, and presents the structured score and its associated risk stratum.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications for triage conversations.** The conversation contains PHI (symptoms, medical history, mental-health status, social context that may emerge during sensitive triage). Some triage conversations include disclosures of intimate-partner violence, sexual-health concerns, substance-use issues, and mental-health crisis. The audit, retention, access-control, and downstream-clinical-workflow integration story has to handle each of these with care and with statutory awareness (for example, mandatory-reporting obligations for some disclosures vary by state and by professional credential of the receiving party).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model cannot reliably stay within scope when the patient asks for diagnosis or treatment recommendations.** Patients frequently ask "do you think this is a heart attack?" or "should I take aspirin?" The bot answers triage questions ("the next step for what you are describing is X") not diagnostic questions ("you have Y"). Maintaining the distinction is a discipline that requires the system prompt, the output safety screening, the institutional review of canonical responses, and the clinical-protocol scoping to all align. None is sufficient alone.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to stop the conversation.** A protocol's question sequence has a defined length. Once the relevant features are captured, the bot computes the recommendation. A general LLM might continue conversing indefinitely, asking irrelevant questions, or sliding into therapeutic chat. The protocol-driven logic encodes the stopping condition; the LLM honors it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Triage Bot Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.5 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, intent classification, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation. The triage bot adds six structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Validated clinical-protocol corpus with full version control and clinician sign-off.** The triage protocols are clinical content. They are owned jointly by the institution's medical director, the nurse-triage operations leadership, and the compliance team. Each protocol is reviewed before adoption, reviewed annually, and re-reviewed when material updates are made. The protocols are versioned; the conversation log records which protocol version was active for any given conversation. Skipping this is the failure mode that turns a triage bot into a clinically-unsafe deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Conservative-by-default acuity logic.** The protocols are designed with conservative bias; the bot's logic enforces it. When the bot is uncertain, when the protocol's decision logic spans multiple acuity levels, when the patient's responses are ambiguous, the recommendation defaults to the higher acuity (or escalates to a nurse). Explicit conservative-bias auditing is part of the deployment review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous emergency-screening across every turn.** The crisis-and-emergency screening runs continuously through the conversation, not just at the start. Every patient utterance is screened for emergency keywords and feature constellations. The screening triggers immediate 911 or 988 routing as appropriate, regardless of where the conversation was in the protocol flow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical-decision-rule computation as deterministic tool.** Clinical-decision rules used in the triage logic (HEART, Wells, Centor, Ottawa, others) run as code with structured inputs and structured outputs. The LLM does not compute the score. The deterministic tool returns the score with the associated risk stratum and the protocol-mapped recommendation. The tool's version is audited.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Nurse-line escalation as architectural primitive, not optional feature.** The bot is deployed with a backstop nurse line. The escalation is a first-class capability, not a fallback. The handoff payload includes the full conversation context, the protocol consulted, the answer set, and the computed recommendation. The nurse picks up where the bot left off; the patient does not start over.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy alignment from day one.** Patient-facing triage tools sit on or close to the FDA Software-as-a-Medical-Device line. Whether the specific deployment is regulated depends on the recommendations the tool produces, the population it serves, the claims the institution makes about it, and the current state of FDA guidance. The institutional regulatory team is involved from architectural design, through clinical-protocol selection, through go-live, through post-market surveillance. The technical architecture supports either a non-regulated deployment (informational scope, with clinician review of outputs in regulated edge cases) or a regulated SaMD deployment (with the appropriate quality-management system, clinical-validation evidence, and post-market obligations) depending on the institutional choice. This recipe's architecture is consistent with either, but the deployment decision is the institution's.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, scope filtering, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Triage Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes triage specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The cost of being wrong is asymmetric and severe.** Under-triage (telling a patient with a true emergency that they can stay home) can be fatal. Over-triage (sending a patient with a low-acuity condition to the ED) is expensive and erodes trust. The protocol logic is calibrated to favor over-triage at the expense of under-triage; the operational metrics monitor both rates with separate thresholds. Aggregate accuracy is not a sufficient metric.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage is multilingual by necessity.** Patients in crisis or in pain seek help in their first language. Multilingual deployment is not a phase-2 enhancement; it is a launch-day requirement for institutions serving non-English-speaking populations. <!-- TODO: verify; CMS and various state Medicaid programs impose language-access requirements on certain payer and provider communications, and institutional policies on language access vary --> Per-language asset development includes validated protocol translations, validated regulatory-disclosure phrasings, validated emergency-instruction phrasings, and per-language calibration of the recommendation language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage requires specific accessibility considerations.** Patients with limited digital literacy, patients with vision impairments using screen readers, patients with cognitive impairments, and patients in acute physical distress may interact with the triage bot differently than the average authenticated app user. Accessibility conformance is not a generic web-accessibility checklist; it is a triage-specific set of design decisions about cognitive load, sentence length, voice-channel availability, and graceful degradation when the patient cannot complete the conversation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage interacts with mandatory-reporting laws.** Some triage conversations surface disclosures (child abuse, elder abuse, intimate-partner violence, certain mental-health emergencies) that trigger statutory reporting obligations for licensed clinical staff. The bot itself is not a licensed clinician. The institution's policy specifies how disclosures are handled when the bot is the receiver: typically, the bot acknowledges, provides safety resources, and routes to a clinical staff member who is a mandatory reporter, with the conversation context attached. <!-- TODO: verify; mandatory-reporting laws vary by state, by professional credential, and by category of disclosure; institutional policies for AI-mediated communications are an emerging area -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage contains pediatric and geriatric edge cases that adult-default protocols miss.** Pediatric triage (Schmitt-Thompson Pediatric is the dominant U.S. nurse-line standard) and geriatric triage (with overlay of frailty, polypharmacy, atypical presentations of common conditions, dementia-mediated communication challenges) require dedicated protocols. <!-- TODO: verify; Schmitt-Thompson protocols include dedicated pediatric and adult versions; the geriatric-specific extensions vary by institution and by triage-tool vendor --> The bot's protocol library includes both; the protocol-selection logic recognizes the patient's age and routes to the appropriate version.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage interacts with social context the bot may not see.** Patients without access to transportation cannot follow "go to the urgent care now" if the urgent care is across town and they have no car. Patients without paid sick leave cannot follow "stay home and rest" if doing so means losing income. Patients in unsafe housing cannot follow "monitor your symptoms at home" if home is the source of the problem. The bot's recommendations are formally clinical, but their feasibility is socially determined. The institution's deployment includes social-determinants-of-health overlays where possible, with care-navigation handoffs for patients whose recommended care level is not reachable for them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage outputs sometimes need to integrate with telehealth and care-navigation tools.** When the bot recommends a telehealth visit, it should be able to schedule the visit (or at least surface availability) rather than just say "schedule a telehealth visit." When the bot recommends an urgent care visit, it should be able to surface the patient's nearest in-network urgent care and that location's current wait time. The integration with the institution's scheduling and care-navigation tools is part of the operational scope.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Triage interacts with the patient's existing care plan.** A patient with an active oncology treatment plan presents to the triage bot with new symptoms that are very likely treatment-related. The bot's protocol selection should account for this. A patient on anticoagulation with a head injury presents to the triage bot with a different acuity profile than the same head injury in a patient not on anticoagulation. The chart-context lookup includes active treatment plans, active medications relevant to the presenting symptom, and any recent visits that may be related.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Telehealth integration is bidirectional.** A patient who has just completed a telehealth visit may present to the triage bot with worsening symptoms. The bot's chart context includes the recent visit. The bot's recommendation may differ accordingly. A patient who completes a triage conversation with a "schedule a telehealth visit" recommendation should have that visit booked or scheduled with the conversation context attached, so the receiving telehealth clinician has the triage data available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome correlation is a long-term commitment.** The triage bot's clinical performance is measured against actual outcomes: did the patient who was told to go to the ED actually go, and did the ED visit reveal a clinically-significant finding? Did the patient who was told to stay home actually stay home, and did they need a higher-acuity visit within 72 hours? The institution commits to this outcome correlation as part of the post-market surveillance. <!-- TODO: verify; outcome correlation for symptom-triage tools is operationally significant work that requires data integration across the institution's encounter records and is rarely fully implemented in early deployments -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability and consent considerations are different from non-triage bots.** Patients consenting to use the triage bot are consenting to interact with a tool that provides care-level recommendations. The consent language is reviewed with legal counsel. The handling of cases where the patient ignores the recommendation (the patient was told to go to 911 and chose to wait until morning) is part of the institutional policy and the audit pathway. The institution's malpractice carrier is part of the policy review. <!-- TODO: verify; specific liability frameworks for AI-mediated triage are an emerging legal area; institutional policies and malpractice-coverage arrangements vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Schmitt-Thompson protocols are the dominant U.S. nurse-line standard.** Schmitt-Thompson has versions for adult and pediatric triage and is licensed by most major U.S. nurse-advice line operators. <!-- TODO: verify; Schmitt-Thompson protocols, developed by Drs. Barton Schmitt and David Thompson, are the most widely used U.S. nurse-line triage protocols and are licensed by ClearTriage and other vendors --> Institutions building their own triage tools generally either license Schmitt-Thompson, license another vendor's protocols (such as the Manchester Triage System or proprietary alternatives), or build institution-specific protocols with clinical-leadership ownership. Building from scratch without a clinical foundation is rare and not recommended.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Manchester Triage System is the international standard for ED in-person triage.** MTS is widely used in European, Latin American, and Asian-Pacific EDs. <!-- TODO: verify; the Manchester Triage System is widely adopted internationally for in-ED triage and is differentiated from nurse-line phone-triage protocols --> Institutions building tools for international deployment may use MTS or its derivatives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The Emergency Severity Index (ESI) is the dominant U.S. ED in-person triage standard.** ESI is the in-ED triage approach used by most U.S. emergency departments. <!-- TODO: verify; ESI is published by ACEP and is widely adopted in U.S. EDs as the in-person triage system --> ESI is not a phone-triage or chat-triage protocol, but it informs the recommendation calibration; a triage tool sending a patient to the ED is implicitly contributing to that ED's ESI workflow, and the tool's recommendation framing should align.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical-decision rules are increasingly used as components of triage logic.** The HEART score for chest pain, the Wells score for pulmonary embolism and DVT, the Centor score for streptococcal pharyngitis, the Ottawa ankle and knee rules, and others are validated rules for stratifying risk in specific presentations. <!-- TODO: verify; HEART, Wells, Centor, Ottawa, and similar rules have published validation studies and documented sensitivity/specificity profiles; specific patient-population applicability varies --> Modern triage architectures invoke these rules as deterministic tools when the protocol calls for them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The FDA's posture on patient-facing triage software continues to evolve.** The 2022 final guidance on Clinical Decision Support software clarified the distinction between regulated and non-regulated software, but patient-facing triage tools generally face more scrutiny than clinician-facing CDS, because the patient cannot independently verify the recommendation against their own clinical judgment. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance on CDS software, including the 2022 final guidance and subsequent updates, continues to evolve; the regulatory status of patient-facing triage tools depends on specific product characteristics and claimed functionality --> Institutions deploying patient-facing triage at scale typically work with FDA-experienced regulatory counsel from the architectural design phase.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle triage Q&A well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps directly to triage. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve protocols, gather chart context, compute clinical-decision rules, and post recommendations; the tools return structured data; the LLM composes a grounded answer that delivers the recommendation. The architecture has been deployed at major payers, integrated delivery networks, and digital-health vendors since roughly 2023.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Conversational triage measurably reduces nurse-line wait times and ED over-utilization in specific populations.** Deployments at major institutions have reported substantial reductions in nurse-line wait times for routine triage cases and modest reductions in low-acuity ED utilization, with both effects strongest in member populations with high digital adoption and in member populations whose alternative was the nurse line rather than the ED. <!-- TODO: verify; specific deflection rates and operational impact figures vary by deployment and are sometimes published in vendor case studies and institutional press; consolidated public statistics are not reliably aggregated -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and disparities in triage are an active research area.** Studies of nurse-line triage have documented variability in recommendations by patient demographics that does not appear to be clinically justified. <!-- TODO: verify; literature on demographic variability in triage decisions includes studies of phone-triage, ED-triage (ESI), and digital-symptom-checker triage; specific findings vary --> AI-mediated triage may inherit, amplify, or correct these disparities. Per-cohort monitoring is essential, and the institutional commitment to equity is reviewed by the compliance and patient-experience teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature in this category.** Several conversational triage vendors operate at major-institution scale, with EHR integration, multilingual support, and regulatory frameworks. <!-- TODO: verify; the commercial vendor landscape continues to evolve --> Most major institutions run a hybrid: build the in-house bot for the routine member-facing journey on the institution's preferred infrastructure, partner with a clinical-protocol vendor for the licensed protocols, and integrate with the institution's nurse-line, telehealth, and care-navigation infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
